<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="116" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,1841,2047]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,304,1912,1938]" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">Diagnosis</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName box="[340,634,1912,1939]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Humboldtia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="1" pageNumber="116" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ponmudiana">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[340,634,1912,1939]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">Humboldtia ponmudiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely similar to 
<emphasis box="[877,1031,1913,1939]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Beddome ex Oliver" authorityYear="1895" box="[877,1028,1913,1939]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Humboldtia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="1" pageNumber="116" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="decurrens">H. decurrens</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but differs in having black coloured bark, densely brown tomentose young shoots, lanceolate or ovate-lanceolate leaflets with densely brown tomentose midribs, sessile or subsessile flowers, fairly large broadly ovate eglandular bracts, connate to middle bracteoles with adaxial glabrous surfaces, fairly large anthers, 1–4 ovuled ovaries and silky tomentose pods with long beak (
<tableCitation box="[1350,1433,2021,2047]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,224,988,1012]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 1. Morphological differences between Humboldtia decurrens and H. ponmudiana" pageId="1" pageNumber="116">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
